<li>Additional S. 3.29 2.11 3.29 1.97 3.69 1.22 sprA Oxygen-regulated invasion protein Oxygen-regulated invasion protein Pathogenicity island 1 effector-protein Pathogenicity island 1 effector-protein Pathogenicity island 1 effector-protein Invasion protein regulator Cell invasion protein t2771 t2772 t2774 t2775 t2776 t2778 t2779 1.79 3.50 3.83 3.89 4.02 3.67 3.83 orgA orgA prgJ prgI prgH hilA iagB 3.90 5.65 6.05 6.15 6.36 6.98 6.64 1.34 1.62 1.43 1.41 1.57 1.54 1.35 Chaperone t2781 t2782 3.06 1.40 3.10 1.56 3.19 2.98 sicP Hypothetical protein 5.62 5.84 6.24 5.70 7.26 6.87 6.72 6.66 6.91 6.61 6.04 6.50 6.86 7.12 6.97 4.54 3.76 7.59 sipF or iacP sipA sipD spaS spaQ spaP spaO spaN spaM spaL or invC spaK or invB invA invE invG invF invH sopD rtsB Acyl carrier protein t2783 t2784 t2785 t2789 t2791 t2792 t2793 t2794 t2795 t2796 t2797 t2798 t2799 t2800 t2801 t2802 t2846 t4220 3.43 3.60 3.87 3.29 3.00 3.25 3.66 3.91 3.83 3.43 4.01 3.34 3.59 3.60 3.84 2.97 4.33 3.58 1.46 1.55 1.48 1.24 1.40 1.43 1.60 1.58 1.76 1.53 1.91 1.40 1.35 1.37 1.27 1.57 1.05 1.99 Pathogenicity island 1 effector-protein Pathogenicity island 1 effector-protein Surface presentation of antigens protein SpaS Virulence-associated secretory protein Surface presentation of antigens protein SpaP Surface presentation of antigens protein SpaO Antigen presentation protein SpaN Virulence-associated secretory protein ATP synthase SpaL Virulence-associated secretory protein Virulence-associated secretory protein Cell invasion protein Virulence-associated secretory protein AraC family transcriptional-regulator Cell adherence/invasion protein Hypothetical protein GerE family regulatory protein 7.33 1.80 2.25 1.20 2.09 1.46 3.83 2.22 2.60 AraC family transcriptional-regulator Lipoprotein Hypothetical protein t4221 t0944 t1774 rtsA lpxR srfA srfB 3.44 1.81 1.88 Hypothetical protein Virulence effector-protein Virulence effector-protein t1208 t1503 t1504 7.02 1.19 1.75 1.64 1.48 1.58 FIG 3 Effects of bile on SPI-1 expression and activity .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=29229736" target="_blank">29229736</a>]<br></li>
<li>Transcriptional and translational fusions with araB under ParaBAD and AraC control were tightly regulated during gene expression ( Dalbey and Wickner , 1985 ; Kuhn and Wickner , 1985 ; Russell et al. , 1989 ; San Millan et al. , 1989 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21871930" target="_blank">21871930</a>]<br></li>
<li>AraC protein can activate transcription from only one position and when pointed in only one direction .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7559322" target="_blank">7559322</a>]<br></li>
<li>Given the relationship to AraC , it is also possible that these three regulators bind to small molecules that affect regulation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17208038" target="_blank">17208038</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , it is possible that AraC regulates transcription from the site within sseD under conditions that derepress SPI2 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>To ascertain whether AraC was directly involved in SPI-1 regulation or merely necessary for AraE permease synthesis , two different approaches were undertaken : Figure 2 Dose-dependent regulation of SPI-1 by L-arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25991823" target="_blank">25991823</a>]<br></li>
<li>If AraC is needed for AraE permease synthesis only , constitutive araE expression should prevent AraCmediated suppression of SPI-1 repression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25991823" target="_blank">25991823</a>]<br></li>
<li>Instead , AraC subunit domains involved in DNA binding appear to be ﬂexible enough to alternate between inverted - and direct-repeat orientations in response to the coinducer D-arabinose ( 5 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7730263" target="_blank">7730263</a>]<br></li>
<li>L-rhamnose catabolic regulons The transcriptional-regulator RhaS in E. coli belongs to the AraC protein family and controls the L-Rha transporter rhaT and the catabolic operon rhaBADU ( Egan and Schleif , 1993 ; Via et al. , 1996 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24391637" target="_blank">24391637</a>]<br></li>
<li>RamA belongs to the AraC transcriptional-activator family , and this gene appears to be speciﬁc for Salmonella serovars and is absent in many other gram-negative microorganisms ; notable exceptions are Klebsiella pneumoniae and Enterobacter species [ 93 -- 95 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19230852" target="_blank">19230852</a>]<br></li>
<li>appears to be species restricted and belongs to the AraC transcriptional-activator family .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14742546" target="_blank">14742546</a>]<br></li>
<li>Only one indirect target gene , isrB , is upregulated 4-fold by both AraC and arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>ygeA and polB are positively regulated by AraC and arabinose due to partial read-through of Rho-independent terminators ( Fig. 2 , 4 , and 5 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>AraC / XylS family members , HilD and HilC , directly activate virulence gene expression independently of HilA in Salmonella typhimurium .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15256548" target="_blank">15256548</a>]<br></li>
<li>This is particularly important for AraC binding upstream of ydeN , since this interaction appears to be completely dependent upon arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , this observation did not necessarily indicate that AraC is involved in L-arabinose repression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25991823" target="_blank">25991823</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , ydeNM is a novel AraC-regulated operon that is directly repressed by AraC in an arabinose-dependent manner .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , we detected no effect of GalR on regulation of ytfQ by AraC ( data not shown ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>Arabinose-independent repression of ytfQ transcription by AraC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>Arabinose-dependent repression of ydeNM transcription by AraC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>Lack of AraC suppressed hilA repression by 0.2 % L-arabinose ( Figure 4A , third column ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25991823" target="_blank">25991823</a>]<br></li>
<li>When araE was expressed constitutively , lack of AraC no longer suppressed hilA repression by L-arabinose ( Figure 4B ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25991823" target="_blank">25991823</a>]<br></li>
<li>Its expression is modulated precisely by its local repressor , AcrR , as well as by global transcriptional-regulators of the AraC family , RamA , MarA , SoxS , and Rob ( Nikaido et al. , 2008 ; Kehrenberg et al. , 2009 ; Pérez et al. , 2012 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=28261566" target="_blank">28261566</a>]<br></li>
<li>AraC requires arabinose for the expression of AraC-activated promoters ( Gallegos et al. , 1997 ; Soisson et al. , 1997 ) , therefore we hypothesized that InvF also required a cofactor for transcriptional activation of sigD and sicA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10692170" target="_blank">10692170</a>]<br></li>
<li>HilD , a member of the AraC family of transcriptional-regulators , induces the expression of HilA ( Schechter et al. , 1999 ; Schechter and Lee , 2001 ; Ellermeier et al. , 2005 ) , an OmpR/ToxRlike transcriptional-regulator , which in turn , activates the expression of InvF ( Lostroh et al. , 2000 ; Lostroh and Lee , 2001 ) , another AraC-like regulator .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=26300871" target="_blank">26300871</a>]<br></li>
<li>Induction of SPI1 effector-proteins requires three transcriptional-regulators of the AraC family : HilD , HilC and RtsA ( Schechter et al. , 1999 ; Ellermeier and Slauch , 2003 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=27341691" target="_blank">27341691</a>]<br></li>
<li>To exclude noise data based on microarray analysis , we considered that genes for which STM1214 ycfR Putative outer membrane protein STM1355 Putative transcription regulator , AraC family STM1472 Putative periplasmic protein expression changed in the presence of both 1 and 4 mM of indole were significantly regulated by indole .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22632036" target="_blank">22632036</a>]<br></li>
<li>AraC bound to L-arabinose activates transcription from the araBAD and araE promoters .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25991823" target="_blank">25991823</a>]<br></li>
<li>Arabinose-induced binding of AraC protein to araI2 activates the araBAD operon promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21871930" target="_blank">21871930</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>As AraC activates araE transcription , suppression in an AraCˉ background might be caused by a decrease of intracellular L-arabinose due to lack of AraE permease .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25991823" target="_blank">25991823</a>]<br></li>
<li>S3 in the supplemental material ) , suggesting that AraC directly represses transcription of ytfQ , albeit weakly .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>We mapped the genome-wide binding of C-terminally FLAG-tagged AraC in S. enterica subsp .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , our data suggest that the overall afﬁnity of AraC for its DNA sites is increased by association with arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>The evidence that L-arabinose needs to be inside the cell to repress SPI-1 raised the possibility that activation of AraC by L-arabinose might be directly responsible for SPI-1 repression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25991823" target="_blank">25991823</a>]<br></li>
<li>This hypothesis is supported by the following observations : Figure 4 Roles of AraE and AraC in SPI-1 regulation by L-arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25991823" target="_blank">25991823</a>]<br></li>
<li>Transport of L-arabinose is necessary to repress SPI-1 ; however , repression is independent of L-arabinose metabolism and of the L-arabinose-responsive regulator AraC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25991823" target="_blank">25991823</a>]<br></li>
<li>The phenomenon described in this study , SPI-1 repression by L-arabinose , is independent of L-arabinose catabolism and of the regulatory protein AraC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25991823" target="_blank">25991823</a>]<br></li>
<li>The prototype regulator AraC is involved in the regulation of arabinose catabolism ; the sugar arabinose binds to AraC and modulates its activity ( 1 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11370771" target="_blank">11370771</a>]<br></li>
<li>SPI-1 repression by L-arabinose is independent of AraC In the bacterial cytoplasm , L-arabinose binds AraC and causes an allosteric change that enables AraC to activate the expression of genes involved in L-arabinose catabolism , including araE ( Schleif 2010 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25991823" target="_blank">25991823</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the absence of arabinose , AraC represses transcription of araBAD and araC by forming a repression loop mediated by dimerization of distally bound AraC monomers ( 5 , 6 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>We demonstrate arabinose-dependent repression of ydeNM by AraC , in contrast to the well-described arabinose-dependent activation of other target genes .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , arabinose-dependent repression of ydeNM by AraC would use the same mechanism as arabinose-dependent activation of araBAD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>We hypothesized that despite the extensive prior work on the AraC regulon , there are likely to be previously undescribed AraC-regulated genes and novel modes of regulation by AraC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>All of the direct regulatory targets are positively regulated by AraC and arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>No direct targets were identiﬁed that are regulated by AraC in the absence of arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , in the absence of L-arabinose , AraC acts as a repressor ( Schleif 2010 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25991823" target="_blank">25991823</a>]<br></li>
<li>This is consistent with our ChIP data showing binding of AraC upstream of ydeN only in the presence of arabinose ( Fig. 1A ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>ChIP/qPCR veriﬁed signiﬁcant association of AraC with all regions tested in the presence of arabinose ( Fig. 1A ; araJ was not tested ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>Association of AraC with all regions was reduced in the absence of arabinose , with no association detected for ydeN ( Fig. 1A ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>To test this hypothesis , we compared the effect of increasing concentrations of -- L-arabinose on the expression of a hilA : : lac fusion in AraA -- -- and AraA AraC backgrounds .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25991823" target="_blank">25991823</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the absence of arabinose , we did not detect AraC association upstream of ydeN ( Fig. 1A ) , nor did we detect any signiﬁcant difference in expression of ydeN or ydeM between wild-type and araC mutant cells in the absence of arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>This strongly suggests the presence of an AraC binding site overlapping the transcription start site , consistent with a role in transcriptional repression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>Perhaps InvF , like AraC , requires a cofactor ( in the case of AraC , arabinose ) ( 13 ) which induces a conformational change in InvF allowing it to-bind to the appropriate promoters .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10438766" target="_blank">10438766</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the arabinose utilization system , cAMP receptor protein ( CRP ) is the transcriptional-regulator responding to cAMP induced by the primary signal ( i.e. , low environmental glucose levels ) , whereas CRP-activated arabinose-responsive protein AraC is the regulator directly binding to the secondary signal ( i.e. , L-arabinose ) ( reviewed in ref .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19091955" target="_blank">19091955</a>]<br></li>
<li>We then introduced plasmid pYA3450 , which carries the asdA gene with ATG start codon transcribed from the PBAD promoter , which is activated by the AraC protein in the presence of arabinose ( 25 ) , into 8276 to yield 8276 ( pYA3450 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18607005" target="_blank">18607005</a>]<br></li>
<li>The phoP gene is transcribed from the PBAD promoter , which is activated by the AraC protein in the presence of arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22144486" target="_blank">22144486</a>]<br></li>
<li>It is conceivable that the N-terminus of InvF , which is considerably smaller than the N-terminus of AraC , could interact with SicA , resulting in the dimerization of InvF .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10692170" target="_blank">10692170</a>]<br></li>
<li>Yet another possibility would be that SicA , like arabinose for AraC , changes the conformation of the putative DNA-binding domains of InvF , resulting in transcriptional activation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10692170" target="_blank">10692170</a>]<br></li>
<li>The more upstream conserved sequence that resembles an AraC binding site falls outside the region predicted by the ChIP-seq data ; hence , it may bind AraC under other growth conditions , e.g. , in the absence of arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>Given the lack of conservation of this putative AraC binding site in other Enterobacteriaceae species and the lack of detectable regulation by AraC at this site , we conclude that the site is unlikely to have regulatory function under the tested growth conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>E. coli AraC activates transcription of the araBAD , araFGH , araE , and araJ transcripts in the presence of its inducer , L-arabinose ( 5 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
