<li>We propose that the DNA binding properties of AraC allow it to-bind at ydeN only in the presence of arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>At the araC-araBAD intergenic region , AraC forms a repression loop in the absence of arabinose due to the dimerization of distally bound AraC mono-mers .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>This conformational change results in gene activation by changing the binding specificity of the carboxyl ( C ) - terminus of the AraC dimer to the arabinose operators , ultimately resulting in the release of a DNA loop structure which prevents transcription .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10692170" target="_blank">10692170</a>]<br></li>
