<li>As members of the AraC family , HilC and HilD monomers are expected to bind to a 17-bp region , in which each helix-turn helix motif binds to 3 - to 6-bp stretches on successive DNA helical turns ( 29 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12107132" target="_blank">12107132</a>]<br></li>
<li>Expression of hilA itself is activated by three AraC family regulators , HilC , HilD , and RtsA ( 25 , 78 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18160484" target="_blank">18160484</a>]<br></li>
<li>Interestingly , a large number of AraC family members are involved in antibiotic resistance , stress response , and carbohydrate metabolism ( 9 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12029036" target="_blank">12029036</a>]<br></li>
<li>AraC / XylS family members , HilD and HilC , directly activate virulence gene expression independently of HilA in Salmonella typhimurium .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15256548" target="_blank">15256548</a>]<br></li>
<li>AraC is highly conserved across the family Entero-bacteriaceae , which includes E. coli and S. enterica .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
<li>These include the so-called LysNMetR regulatory protein family , the AraC protein family , the iron response-regulator Fur family , and two-component regulatory systems .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11370771" target="_blank">11370771</a>]<br></li>
<li>Other down regulated genes included t4221 , a member of the AraC family transcriptional regulator family and t4220 , a GerE family regulatory protein .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24386394" target="_blank">24386394</a>]<br></li>
<li>Apart from LTTRs , SEN4086 , which belongs to the family of AraC transcriptional regulators , showed signiﬁcantly reduced expression in LP strains .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24271167" target="_blank">24271167</a>]<br></li>
<li>Not surprisingly , therefore , many members of the AraC family are known to be involved in virulence gene expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11370771" target="_blank">11370771</a>]<br></li>
<li>In contrast , our data indicate that most members of the AraC regulon are conserved in this family .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24272778" target="_blank">24272778</a>]<br></li>
